                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d891">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/13015.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Vice
                        Consul <persName type="to">Silliman</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 28, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your August 26. Say to General Carranza that we are sending to Mexico an American
                    named Hall, personal friend of Zapata, with the view to bringing about a meeting
                    between Carranza and Zapata and for the purpose of urging upon Zapata the use of
                    peaceful and constitutional methods. It would hardly seem wise for Carranza to
                    leave the capital for a conference, but he ought to make every effort to secure
                    a reconciliation.</p>
                <p>The President is also sending a personal representative, Mr. Fuller, to confer
                    with Carranza. Fuller and Hall will sail for Vera Cruz to-morrow. Please meet
                    them at Vera Cruz and give them such information as will aid them in their
                    work.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">W. J. Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
